=== NPCI Dispute Resolution Mechanism (DRM) Entry Guide for Wrong Transfers ===

What is DRM? NPCI's Dispute Resolution Mechanism is the inter-bank complaint escalation for UPI wrong transfers. You cannot directly submit a DRM complaint — your bank (PSP) does it on your behalf.

Step 1 — Within 3 working days of the wrong transfer:
  • Lodge a complaint at your bank's grievance portal / branch. Get a complaint ref number (this becomes your DRM ticket id).
  • Use the Refund Radar template 'wrong_transfer_bank_request' to write your bank.

Step 2 — Insist on DRM ticket creation:
  • Your bank must raise a 'DRM-INC' (Dispute) ticket against the beneficiary bank via NPCI's Bank Dispute Resolution (BDR) portal.
  • DRM ticket id will look like 'BDR-XXXXX-XXXXX' — ask your bank for it.

Step 3 — Beneficiary bank response:
  • Beneficiary bank contacts their customer and asks for consent. If the customer consents, funds are returned via UPI return.
  • If the customer does NOT consent within the DRM response window (typically 7 working days), the bank has to inform you that the recall has failed.

Step 4 — If recall fails:
  • File an FIR if the wrong transfer is fraud (use Refund Radar 'wrong_transfer_cybercell_complaint').
  • For civil recovery, file a suit for 'money had and received' / Section 72 of the IT Act, 2000.

Step 5 — Banking Ombudsman only if YOUR bank failed to file the DRM complaint.
  • File at https://cms.rbi.org.in under 'Deficiency in service — failure to lodge DRM within reasonable time'.

Important caveat (RBI / NPCI): wrong transfers depend on beneficiary consent. There is no automatic refund right. Compensation is NOT payable for customer-caused wrong transfers, only for bank-side defects.

Key info to keep ready while raising DRM:
  • UTR: {UTR}
  • Amount: Rs. {AMOUNT}
  • Date: {TXN_DATE}
  • Payee VPA: {VPA_PAYEE}
  • Your VPA: {VPA}
  • Your bank complaint ref: {TICKET_NO}
  • Your bank: {BANK_NAME}
  • Beneficiary bank: {BENEFICIARY_BANK}

